n Pritchard (USA) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2002''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2003''' Men || Josh Angulo (USA) || Example || -\n|-\n| '''2003''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2004''' Men || Scott McKercher (AUS) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2004''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Motoko Sato (JPN) || -\n|-\n| '''2005''' Men || Kauli Seadi (BRA) || Alex Mussolini (ESP) || -\n|-\n| '''2005''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Jennifer Henderson (USA) || -\n|-\n| '''2006''' Men || Kevin Pritchard (USA) || Josh Angulo (USA) || -\n|-\n| '''2006''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || -\n|-\n| '''2007''' Men || Kauli Seadi (BRA) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2007''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2008''' Men || Kauli Seadi (BRA) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2008''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2009''' Men || Josh Angulo (USA) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2009''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2010''' Men || Victor Fern\u00e1ndez (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2010''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || - || -\n|-\n| '''2011''' Men || Philip K\u00f6ster (GER) || Camille Juban (GDL) || Nathan Mershon (USA)\n|-\n| '''2011''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Junko Naghoshi (JPN) || Ingrid Larouche (CAN)\n|-\n| '''2012''' Men || Philip K\u00f6ster (GER) || Bernd Roediger (USA) || Camille Juban (DGL)\n|-\n| '''2012''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Junko Naghoshi (JPN) || Ingrid Larouche (CAN)\n|-\n| '''2013''' Men || Marcilio Browne (BRA) || Levi Siver (USA) + Bernd Roediger (USA) || Camille Juban (DGL)\n|-\n| '''2013''' Women || Daida Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Junko Naghoshi (JPN) || Ingrid Larouche (CAN)\n|-\n| '''2014''' Men || Thomas Traversa (FRA) || Morgan Noireaux (USA) + Boujmaa Guilloul (MOR) || Kevin Pritchard (USA)\n|-\n| '''2014''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Ingrid Larouche (CAN)\n|-\n| '''2015''' Men || Philip K\u00f6ster (GER) || Morgan Noireaux (USA) || Camille Juban (DGL)\n|-\n| '''2015''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Sarah Hauser (NCL)\n|-\n| '''2016''' Men || Victor Fern\u00e1ndez (ESP) || Kevin Pritchard (USA) || Boujmaa Guiloull (MOR)\n|-\n| '''2016''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Sarah-Quita Offringa (ARU) || Sarah Hauser (NCL)\n|-\n| '''2017''' Men || Philip K\u00f6ster (GER) || Morgan Noireaux (USA) || Morgan Noireaux (USA)\n|-\n| '''2017''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Sarah Hauser (NCL) || Annamaria Zollet (ITA)\n|-\n| '''2018''' Men || Victor Fern\u00e1ndez (ESP) || Camille Juban (GDL || Antoine Martin (GDL)\n|-\n| '''2018''' Women || Iballa Ruano Moreno (ESP) || Sarah Hauser (NCL) || Sarah Hauser (NCL)\n|-\n| '''2019''' Men || Philip K\u00f6ster (GER) || Antoine Martin (GDL) || Antoine Martin (GDL)\n|-\n| '''2019''' Women || Sarah-Quita Offringa (ARU) || Sarah-Quita Offringa (ARU) || Maria Andr\u00e9s (ESP)\n|} <ref name=\"auto3\"/> <ref name=\"auto4\"/> <ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===Wave Riding===\nWave riding is a form of surfing with the extra speed and power afforded by the sail. It is strongly connected to its roots in surfing in style and culture. It involves the rider performing a series of bottom turns, top turns, and cutbacks whilst riding an unbroken wave back to the shore.  Top wave sailors are able to incorporate aerial moves into their wave riding and will use overhanging wave lips to launch themselves out in front of the wave in spectacular giant aerials.\n\n===Wave Jumping===\nWave jumping involves stunts of varying levels of difficulty which are performed after the rider has jumped from the peak of an unbroken wave. These are commonly referred to as aerial moves and include both forward rotation and backward rotations. The rider and his equipment rotate, doing single & double rotations and jumps where the sailor contorts his or her body and equipment. Recent innovations have included combining moves whilst airborne and, for the first time in 2008, one professional sailor, Ricardo Campello, has made attempts at a triple forward loop during a 2008 PWA competition.\n\n=== Big Wave Riding===\nAt the most extreme end of the sport is Big Wave Riding which means riders on waves faces over 30 feet high. The most popular place for this is on the north shore of Maui at place called Pe'ahi to the local Hawaiians, and known as JAWS to the rest of the world. The biggest waves here can be up to 60 foot faces. It breaks only in the winter months from late October to March. Other famous big wave locations include Nazar\u00e9 in Portugal. Famous contemporary big wave riders include Kai Lenny, Marcilio Browne, Robby Swift, Sarah Hauser, Jason Polakow, and Robby Naish.\n\n===Storm Riding===\nThe most famous storm riding event is known as The Red Bull Storm Chase. It occurs only when there is a massive storm forecast with winds over 60 knots and giant waves over 20 feet. It is an invitational event and is extremely dangerous. The most recent winner was West Australian Jaeger Stone.\n\n===Freestyle===\n\nFreestyle is a timed event which is judged. The competitor who has the greatest repertoire, or manages to complete most stunts, wins. Freestyle is about show and competitors are judged on their creativity. Both the difficulty and the number of tricks make up the final score. Sailors who perform tricks on both tacks (port and starboard), and perform the tricks fully planing score higher marks. High scoring moves include Shaka, Burner (funnel ponch), Double Forward Loops, the Funnell (invented by freestyle champion [[Windsurfing#International stars|Ricardo Campello]] in memory of Andy Funnell), the Chachoo and the Clew First Puneta (switch stance [[Spock (windsurfing)|Spock]]), Eslider, and [[Flaka]]. The latest freestyle windsurfing has been well documented in the film ''Four Dimensions''. For novice windsurfers, low-wind freestyle tricks are an appropriate start, such as sailing backwards with the fin out of the water, or transitioning from a sailing stance to sitting on the board while continuing to sail.\n\n===Big Air===\nCompetitors compete to see who can record the highest jump or maneuver.  A 3D accelerometer is worn to measure and record heights of the jumps.  Xensr is a manufacturer of 3D accelerometers and promoter of the Big Air competition.  It is a popular discipline on the Columbia River near the town of Hood River, Oregon, USA.\n\n==International Stars==\n<!-- This section is linked from Windsurfing -->\n\n===Top Men===\n* '''[[Robby Naish]]''' (USA): one of the first windsurfing champions to gain international fame, he dominated the early years of competition in the 1970s and 1980s. World Champion from 1976 to 1979, Overall World Champion from 1983 to 1987, and Wave World Champion in 1988, 1989, and 1991 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Robby_Naish&oldid=940152653|title=Robby Naish|date=February 10, 2020|via=Wikipedia}}</ref>.\n* '''[[Bj\u00f6rn Dunkerbeck]]''' (ESP): the successor to Naish, he dominated international professional competition from the late 1980s and throughout the 1990s. Twelve-time PWA Overall World Champion in a row. He won the Professional Windsurfers Association (PWA) World Championships for Slalom, Wave, Course Racing and Overall, a record forty one times in total.[1][2] '''He is credited in the Guinness Book of World Records as the most successful athlete of all time with 41 World Titles''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Bj%C3%B6rn_Dunkerbeck&oldid=915612928|title=Bj\u00f6rn Dunkerbeck|date=September 14, 2019|via=Wikipedia}}</ref>.\n* '''Mike Waltz''' (USA): first to put a windsurfing sail on a surfboard and sail the famed Hookipa beach on Maui in 1979. This shifted the entire sport from the original {{convert|12|ft|cm|order=flip|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} long boards to the shorter boards ridden today.  Mike also hosted Maui's first professional wave sailing and slalom event in 1981, which became the foundation of the windsurfing world tour, and Maui became the mecca for the sport both as a design center and a training ground for professionals <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.windsurf.co.uk/mike-waltze-windsurfing-maui/|title=MIKE WALTZE WINDSURFING MAUI|date=October 21, 2017|website=Windsurf Magazine}}</ref> .\n* '''Arnaud de Rosnay''' (FRA): Photographer, and windsurfing adventurer. Best known for his open-ocean windsurfing exploits, and numerous long distance crossings in conflict areas. Lost at sea in November 1984 in the Taiwan Strait.  He created the first speedsailing event in 1981, a 40&nbsp;km race in Maui.  80 competitors participated in the first event, Arnaud de Rosnay finishing second behind Robby Naish. He is also credited with the invention of Kite surfing (1980) and land sailing (Speedsail 1977), even crossing a distance of 1380&nbsp;km in the Sahara in 1979 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Arnaud_de_Rosnay&oldid=166634131|title=Arnaud de Rosnay|date=January 22, 2020|via=Wikipedia}}</ref>.\n* Peter Boyd (USA): Moved to Maui in 1980, and pioneered several windsurfing maneuvers. He was the first to perform an aerial loop, which was considered impossible by many.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} The maneuver opened the door to a variety of aerial loop variations, including the push loop and double rotations. While innovation was his main focus, Boyd did defeat World champion, Ken Winner several times at International competitions <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://internationalwindsurfingtour.com/30-years-of-the-aloha-classic-a-history-and-philosophy/|title=30 YEARS OF THE ALOHA CLASSIC: A HISTORY AND PHILOSOPHY - International Windsurfing Tour-Inspiring the Future of Our Sport|first=Russ|last=Faurot|date=October 29, 2014}}</ref>.\n* '''Stephan van den Berg''' (NED), World Champion 1979\u20131983, gold medal winner first Olympic windsurfing contest in Los Angeles, California in 1984.\n* '''Guy Cribb''' (GBR): four times world championships runner-up in the 1990s. 13 UK champion titles.\n* '''Mark Angulo''' (USA): Early pioneer of many wave sailing moves, including the wave-face 360 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mauitime.com/news/surf-sports/interview-with-maui-surfer-mark-angulo-november-11-1997-2/|title=Interview with Maui Surfer Mark Angulo \u2013 November 11, 1997|website=mauitime.com}}</ref>.\n* '''Jason Polakow''' (AUS): PWA Wave World Champion, 1997, 1998. First windsurfer to ride big wave of Nazare, in Portugal <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/jason-polakow|title=jason polakow - Sport News Headlines - Nine Wide World of Sports|website=wwos.nine.com.au}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tracksmag.com.au/news/10-tracks-surfing-facts-424757|title=10 Tracks Surfing Facts|website=Tracks}}</ref>.\n* '''Kevin Pritchard''' (USA): PWA Wave World Champion, 2006, PWA 1st overall ranking, 2000. Aloha Classic Champion 2016.\n* '''Nik Baker''' (GBR): Three-time PWA Wave World 2nd Place, six-time Indoor World Champion.\n* '''Josh Angulo''' (USA): Mark's younger brother and early pioneer of Cape Verde <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfersjournal.com/product-tag/josh-angulo/|title=Josh Angulo|website=The Surfers Journal}}</ref>.\n* '''Tonky Frans''' (BON): 3rd world freestyle 2009. 1st Midwinters Merit Island Freestyle Competition in 2001.\n* '''Jean-Patrick van der Wolde''' (NED): IFCA Junior World Champion of 2011.\n* '''Dave Kalama''' (USA): Although known for his big wave surfing and stand-up surfing accomplishments, he is an outstanding windsurfer and invented the move known as the Goiter <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Dave_Kalama&oldid=942506798|title=Dave Kalama|date=February 25, 2020|via=Wikipedia}}</ref>. \n* '''Antoine Albeau''' (FRA): 22 times World Champion in various disciplines: Formula windsurfing, Super X, Freestyle, Slalom, Race, Speed, Overall. Holder of the windsurf speed record 53.27 knots, on the 5th of November 2015.\n* '''Josh Stone''' (USA): freestyle pioneer, inventor of the Spock, PWA Freestyle World Champion in 1999, 2000 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanwindsurfer.com/articles/romancing-josh-stone/|title=ROMANCING: Josh Stone|date=December 5, 2015|website=American Windsurfer}}</ref>.\n* '''Ricardo Campello''' (VEN): a freestyle innovator, he created many difficult moves, PWA Freestyle World Champion in 2003, 2004, and 2005.\n* '''Kauli Seadi''' (BRA): pioneered freestyle maneuvers in wave competition. Ranked first in PWA Wave competition in 2005, 2007, 2008 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.windsurf.co.uk/featured/perspective-kauli-seadi/|title=PERSPECTIVE - KAULI SEADI|website=Windsurf Magazine}}</ref>.\n* '''Gollito Estredo''' (VEN): 9 time PWA Freestyle World Champion 2005, 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2014, 2015, 2017, 2018, innovator of new tricks.\n* '''Thomas Traversa''' (FRA): PWA Wave World Champion 2014, 1st RedBull Storm Chase.\n* '''Steven van Broeckhoven'''(NED): European Freestyle Champion 2010, PWA Freestyle World Champion 2011.\n* [[:de:'''Philip K\u00f6ster|Philip K\u00f6ster''']] (GER): PWA Wave World Champion 2011, 2012, 2015, and 2019.\n* '''V\u00edctor Fern\u00e1ndez''' (ESP): PWA Wave World Champion 2010, 2016, and 2018.\n* '''Boujmaa Guilloul''' (MOR): 1st PWA event Hawaii Pro wave 2004, 2014 1st AWT Pro Fleet - Starboard Severne Aloha Classic, 9th PWA Starboard Severne Aloha Classic, 2010 ranked 20th overall PWA Wave, 2009 8th Cabo Verde Wave, 2008 ranked 19th overall PWA Wave, 2007 ranked 14th Wave, came 5th in Guincho.\n* '''Camille Juban''' (GDE): 2 times Aloha Classic Champion 2011 and 2018. 3 time AWT overall Pro Men Wavesailing champion 2012, 2013 and 2015.\n* '''Bernd Roediger''' (USA): 2 times Aloha Classic Champion 2012 and 2013.\n* '''Frank Ervin''': Formula windsurfing lightweight world champion.\n* '''Morgan Noireaux''' (USA): 3 times Aloha Classic Champion 2014, 2015 and 2017. IWT overall Pro Men Wavesailing champion 2017.\n* '''Antoine Martin''' (GDE): Aloha Classic Champion 2019, 2 x IWT Wave Champion 2018, 2019, French National Wave Champion 2019.\n\n===Top Women===\n* '''Jill Boyer''' (USA): World Wave Champion 1984.\n* '''Julie de Werd''' (USA): World Wave Champion 1984.\n* '''Clare Seeger''' (GBR): One of the top female windsurfers in the 1980s. She was also No 1 British Champion for 10yrs and was the first Briton to obtain and overall World Title. Clare won numerous events around the World until finally settling in Hawaii. She was one of the first women who did forward loops, push loops and was the first person to do a double back loop at Ho'okipa,Maui, Hawaii.\n* '''Lisa Penfield''' (USA): Freestyle World Champion 1985, multiple Championships from 1981\u2013 1986.\n* '''Dana Dawes''' (USA): World Wave Champion 1986, 1987.\n* '''Nathalie Siebel''' (FRA): World Wave Champion 1986, 1988, 1990, 1992, 1994.\n* '''Angela Cocheran''' (USA): World Wave Champion 1989, 1991 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yachtsandyachting.com/news/216009/IWT-Chile-Topocalma-Infernal-day-2-of-heats|title=IWT Chile Topocalma Infernal - Day 2 of heats|website=www.yachtsandyachting.com}}</ref>.\n* '''Natalie Lelievre''' (FRA): overall World Champion, 1984, 1985. World Wave Champion 1995, 1996, 1997.\n* '''Barbara Kendall''' (NZ): 3 time Olympian representing New Zealand with Gold in Barcelona 1992, Silver in Atlanta 1996, Bronze in Sydney 2000 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Barbara_Kendall&oldid=906863633|title=Barbara Kendall|date=July 18, 2019|via=Wikipedia}}</ref>.\n* '''Jessica Crisp''' (AUS): 5 time Olympian representing Australia. PWA Overall World Champion 1994. PWA World Wavesailing Champion 1993 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womensportreport.com/jessica-crisp-wins-the-australian/wn/7294|title=Jessica Crisp wins The Australian RSX Windsurfing National CHampionships|website=Women's Sport - Women's sport news}}</ref>.\n* '''Karin Jaggi''' (GER): multiple PWA World Champion in freestyle, wave, speed competition, 1990s and 2000s. World Wave Champion 1998.\n*[http://www.morenotwins.com '''Daida Ruano Moreno'''] (ESP): PWA Wave World Champion, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2013. Freestyle World Champion 2003\u20132006.\n* [http://www.morenotwins.com '''Iballa Ruano Moreno'''] (ESP): PWA Wave World Champion, 1999, 2006, 2007, 2012, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018. Twin sister of Daida Moreno.\n* '''Sarah-Quita Offringa''' (ARU): 17-time World Champion (12 Freestyle, 4 Slalom & 1 Wave), PWA World Wave Champion 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Windsurfing}}\n\nSimilar sports:\n*[[Kite ice skating]] \u2014 ice skater propelled by kite\n*[[Kitesurfing]] \u2014 surfer propelled by kite\n*[[Land sailing]] \u2014 yacht with wheels\n*[[Land windsurfing]] \u2014 on large skateboard, propelled by sail\n*[[Surfing]]\n*[[Wakeboarding]] \u2014 water skiing on a board instead of skis\n*[[Waterskiing]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=Windsurfing |commons=Category:Windsurfing |b= |n= |q= |s= |v= |voy=Windsurfing |species=no |d=no |display=Windsurfing }}\n*{{Curlie|Sports/Water_Sports/Windsurfing/}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070312031133/http://dwsv.net/regattakalender/kalender_anzeige.php?category_12=1&Submit=Liste+filtern International Race Calendar Formula Windsurfing including results, equipment list, reports, photos and videos]\n*[http://www.formulawindsurfing.org Official Formula Class Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070312031020/http://dwsv.net/regattakalender/kalender_anzeige.php?category_11=1&Submit=Liste+filtern International Event Calendar Slalom Racing with results, reports, photos and videos]\n*[http://www.windsurfquest.net Windsurf Quest Location Guide and Social Media Site]\n*[http://www.akvq.ca Quebec Windsurfing Association (Canada)]\n*[http://www.raceboard.org.uk UK raceboard organizatio