{"title_page": "2019 Canisius Golden Griffins men's soccer team", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n\n[[Category:Canisius Golden Griffins seasons]]\n[[Category:2019 Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference men's soccer season|Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n[[Category:American men's college soccer teams 2019 season|Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in New York (state)|Canisius Golden Griffins men's soccer]]\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n\n[[Category:2019 Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference men's soccer season|Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n[[Category:American men's college soccer teams 2019 season|Canisius Golden Griffins]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in New York (state)|Canisius Golden Griffins men's soccer]]\n", "name_user": "18pittsone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019_Canisius_Golden_Griffins_men%27s_soccer_team&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Transatlantic crossing", "text_new": "{{For|other uses of the term Transatlantic|Transatlantic (disambiguation){{!}}Transatlantic}}\n\n'''Transatlantic crossings''' are passages of passengers and cargo across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] between [[Europe]] or [[Africa]] and the [[Americas]]. The majority of passenger traffic is across the North Atlantic between [[Western Europe]] and [[North America]].  Centuries after the dwindling of sporadic [[Viking]] trade with [[Markland]], a regular and lasting transatlantic [[trade route]] was established in 1566 with the Spanish [[Spanish treasure fleet|West Indies fleets]], following the [[Voyages of Christopher Columbus]].\n\n== By sea ==\n{{Main|List of crossings of the Atlantic Ocean}}\nPrior to the 19th century, transatlantic crossings were undertaken in [[sailing ship]]s, and the journeys were time-consuming and often perilous. The first trade route across the Atlantic was inaugurated by Spain a few decades after the European [[Discovery of the Americas]], with the establishment of the [[Spanish treasure fleet|West Indies fleets]] in 1566, a convoy system that regularly linked its territories in the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain|Americas]] with Spain for over two centuries. [[Portugal]] created a similar maritime route between its ports in [[Colonial Brazil|Brazil]] and the Portuguese mainland. Other colonial powers followed, such as [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Britain]], [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]], as they colonized the [[New World]].\n\nTransatlantic crossings became faster, safer, and more reliable with the advent of [[steamship]]s in the 19th century.  Grand [[ocean liner]]s began making regularly scheduled crossings, and soon it became a symbol of national and company status to build the largest, fastest, and most luxurious ocean liner for transatlantic crossings. The United States, United Kingdom, France, Germany and Italy built the most famous ocean liners.  Examples of some famous transatlantic liners are [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']] (had only made one voyage that was unsuccessful due to striking an iceberg),  {{RMS|Lusitania}}, {{RMS|Mauretania|1906|6}}, {{RMS|Olympic}}, {{SS|Rex}}, {{SS|America|1939|6}}, {{SS|United States}}, {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, {{SS|\u00cele de France}}, {{SS|Normandie}}, {{RMS|Queen Elizabeth}}, {{SS|France|1961|6}}, ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'', and {{RMS|Queen Mary 2}}.\n\nThe [[Blue Riband]] is awarded for the record fastest crossing by [[transatlantic liner]].  The current eastbound record was set by the American ocean liner ''[[SS United States|United States]]'' in July 1952: the ship made the crossing in  3 days, 10 hours, 40 minutes. ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' has awarded world records to various classes such as luxury liners, sail boats, and rowing boats.  Because of the shape of the continents and the assistance (or resistance) of ocean currents, the Eastbound crossing is quicker than the Westbound crossing.\n\nDuring World War II the transatlantic crossing was very important for the United Kingdom as much of Europe had been taken over by Germany and its allies preventing trade and supplies; the struggle is known as the [[Battle of the Atlantic]].\n\n===Crossings in small vessels===\n\n====Yacht=====\nThe late Tom Gentry set nearly every powerboat speed record in existence. His passion to win power boating's most coveted honor, the Blue Riband for the fastest passage across the Atlantic, drove him to design and build the 112', 11,500 horsepower Gentry Eagle. In 1989, he and a crew of five including his son, Norman Gentry, shattered the transatlantic crossing record and brought the honor back to the United States. Gentry took the Blue Riband away from the British airline and music tycoon Richard Branson. His record setting time of 62 hours & 7 minutes bested Sir Richard Branson's record by an astonishing 23%.\n\n\n====Zodiac====\nIn 1952, [[Alain Bombard]] crossed the Atlantic from East to West, spending 113 days adrift in a [[Zodiac Marine & Pool|Zodiac]], ''L'H\u00e9r\u00e9tique''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bombard|first=Alain|title=The Voyage of the Heretique|date=1953|publisher=Simon and Schuster}}</ref>\n\n====Rafts====\nIn 1956, [[L\u2019\u00c9gar\u00e9 II|Henri Beaudout]] crossed the Atlantic from West to East, from [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], on a raft of wood and rope, ''[[L\u2019\u00c9gar\u00e9 II]]'', in 88 days.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadden|first=Marie|title=Three Canadians, two kittens, one raft: A little-known journey across the Atlantic|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/three-canadians-two-kittens-one-raft-a-little-known-journey-across-the-atlantic/article4462515/|accessdate=19 May 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, [[Thor Heyerdahl]] crossed the Atlantic in ''Ra II'', a [[papyrus]] raft built to an [[Ancient Egyptian]] design. This voyage followed an unsuccessful attempt the previous year in his first raft, ''Ra I''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heyerdahl |first=Thor |title=The Ra Expeditions |date=1972 |page= |isbn=0-14-003462-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the [[junk raft]], ''[[Son of Town Hall]]'', crossed the North Atlantic Ocean.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Son of Town Hall, First Raft made of Scrap to Cross the North Atlantic Ocean\n  | publisher = The Floating Neutrinos\n  | date = May 30, 2006\n  | url =  http://www.floatingneutrinos.com/son%20of%20town%20hall/chronology.htm\n  | accessdate = Sep 30, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Anthony Smith and the Antiki crossed the Atlantic.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Across the Atlantic - in a garden shed\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url =  http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2971402/Across-Atlantic-garden-shed-84-year-olds-settle-Saga-cruise-ancient-mariner-ideas.html\n  | accessdate = Mar 2, 2015}}\n</ref>\n\n==== Rowing and paddling====\nOn June 13, 2003, the French rower [[Maud Fontenoy]] started an eastward crossing of the Atlantic from [[Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon]]. She reached [[A Coru\u00f1a]] in Spain on October 10, becoming the first woman to accomplish this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maudfontenoyfondation.com/en/ses-traversees-et-son-tour-du-monde.html |website=Fontenroy Foundation|title=Ses-traversees-et-son-tour-du-monde}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the [[Vivaldi Atlantic 4]] broke the previous rowing record of 55 days and setting a new record of 39 days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rowing the Atlantic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series10/week3_vivaldi_atlantic_rowing.shtml |accessdate=29 August 2019 |agency=BBC |date=25 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2010, the Polish [[sexagenarian]] [[Aleksander Doba]] was the first recorded individual to complete a non-stop transatlantic crossing by [[kayak]]. He departed [[Dakar, Senegal]] and arrived in Brazil 99 days later.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/playbook/2011/02/epic-kayak-guy/ | title=64-Year-Old Kayaker Completes Trans-Atlantic Voyage | work=Wired | date=February 10, 2011 | accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref>\n=====Sail=====\n{{main|Transatlantic sailing record}}\n[[Image:Banque populaire5-003.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Banque Populaire V]], current record holder]]\nDuring the second half of the 19th century, more and more leisurely Atlantic crossings started to take place, especially with larger and more luxurious sailing yachts. Over the last century sailing has become more popular, and more accessible. What used to be an imposingly vast ocean has turned into an increasingly popular passage for ocean adventure travellers. With modern well-equipped boats, it has become a safer and more feasible undertaking than it was back in the day. Hundreds of sailing yachts make the Atlantic Ocean crossing each year. Most boats travel the North Atlantic starting from Europe to the Caribbean or South America. Some boats make the passage from Africa to the other side. From the Americas, boats mostly go to Europe. Several different routes exist. The most popular route is the North Atlantic circle, driven by the season and trade winds: the Southern route goes from east to west and the Northern route from west to east. A small but increasing number of yachts also make a high latitude voyage like the North West passage or cross the South Atlantic from Africa to Brazil <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoceanpreneur.com/books |website=Oceanpreneur|title=Ocean Nomad: The Atlantic Sailing Crew Guide}}</ref>\n\n=====Transatlantic rowing races=====\n{{Main|Atlantic Rowing Race}}\nIn 1997, the first East\u2013West Atlantic Rowing Race took place, running from the [[Canary Islands]] to the [[Caribbean]]. It now runs once every two years or so.{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 2006, the first West\u2013East North Atlantic Rowing Race took place, running from [[New York City]] to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]] in the [[UK]].{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Transatlantic flights==\n{{Main|Transatlantic flight}}\nTransatlantic flight surpassed ocean liners as the predominant mode of crossing the Atlantic in the mid 20th century.  In 1919, the American [[NC-4]] became the first [[airplane]] to cross the Atlantic (but in multiple stages). Later that year, a British [[Vickers Vimy]] piloted by [[Alcock and Brown]] made the first non-stop transatlantic flight from [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] to [[Ireland]]. Also in 1919, the British were the first to cross the Atlantic in an [[airship]] when the [[R33 class airship|R34]] captained by Major George Herbert Scott of the [[Royal Air Force]] with his crew and passengers flew from East Fortune, Scotland  to Mineola, Long Island, covering a distance of about {{convert|3000|smi|km}} in about four and a half days; he then made a return trip to England, thus also completing the first double crossing of the Atlantic (east\u2013west\u2013east). The first aerial crossing of the South Atlantic was made by the Portuguese naval aviators [[Gago Coutinho]] and [[Sacadura Cabral]] in 1922. Coutinho and Cabral flew from [[Lisbon, Portugal]], to [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil in stages, using three different [[Fairey III]] biplanes, and they covered a distance of {{convert|8383|km}} between 30 March and 17 June. The first night-time crossing of the Atlantic was accomplished during 16\u201317 April 1927 by the Portuguese aviators [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Sarmento de Beires|Sarmento de Beires]], Jorge de Castilho and Manuel Gouveia, flying from the [[Bijag\u00f3s Archipelago]], [[Portuguese Guinea]], to [[Fernando de Noronha]], Brazil in the ''Argos'', a [[Dornier Do J|Dornier Wal]] flying boat. In May 1927, [[Charles Lindbergh]] made the first solo non-stop transatlantic flight in an airplane (between [[New York City]] and [[Paris]]). The second solo piloting, and the first to carry a passenger, was [[Clarence Duncan Chamberlin]] on June 6, 1927. [[Edward R. Armstrong]] proposed a string of anchored \"seadromes\" to refuel planes in a crossing.\n\nThe first serious attempt to take a share of the transatlantic passenger market away from the ocean liners was undertaken by [[Germany]]. In the 1930s, Germany crossed the Atlantic with [[Zeppelin]]s that could carry about 60 passengers in a similar luxurious style to the ocean liners. However, the [[Hindenburg disaster|''Hindenburg'' disaster]] in 1937 put an end to transatlantic Zeppelin flights.\n\nOn June 1, 1944, two [[K class blimp|K-class blimps]] from Blimp Squadron ZP-14 of the [[United States Navy]] (USN) completed the first transatlantic crossing by [[Blimp|non-rigid airships]]. The two K-ships (K-123 and K-130) left [[South Weymouth Naval Air Station|South Weymouth, MA]] on May 28, 1944 and flew approximately 16 hours to [[Naval Station Argentia]], Newfoundland.  From Argentia, the blimps flew approximately 22 hours to [[Lajes Field]] on Terceira Island in the Azores.  The final leg of the first transatlantic crossing was about a 20-hour flight from the Azores to [[Kenitra Airport|Craw Field]] in Port Lyautey ([[Kenitra]]), French [[Morocco]].<ref>Kline, R. C. and Kubarych, S. J., Blimpron 14 Overseas, 1944, Naval Historical Center, Navy Yard, Washington, D. C.</ref><ref>https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fbd712_4eac320cdad44dd68701e9cecad8e446.pdf</ref>\n\nBeginning in the 1950s, the predominance of ocean liners began to wane when larger, [[jet engine|jet]]-powered airplanes began carrying passengers across the ocean in less and less time.  The speed of crossing the ocean therefore became more important than the style of crossing it.  The maturing passenger [[Jet Age]] starting with the [[Boeing 707]] reduced the typical crossing time between [[London]] and [[New York City]] to between 6.5 and 8 hours, depending on weather conditions.  By the 1970s, supersonic [[Concorde]] airplanes could connect the two cities in less than 4 hours, and only one ocean liner, ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' remained on the transatlantic route for those who favored the slower style of travel. \n\nThe economics of commercial transatlantic flying have evolved markedly since the 1950s; the introduction of [[Wide-body aircraft|widebody]] airliners (such as the [[Boeing 747]] and [[Douglas DC-10]]) in the early 1970s made affordable transatlantic travel to the masses a reality.  Since the 1990s, the high [[reliability engineering|reliability]] of modern jet engines has meant that twin engine jet aircraft such as the [[Boeing 767]], [[Boeing 777]] and [[Airbus A330]] have largely taken over on transatlantic routes from quad-engine jets, whilst the supersonic Concorde was ultimately doomed by its high running costs, leading to its retirement in 2003.  Since the late 1990s, single aisle, narrow body jet airliners (starting with the [[Boeing 757]], and more recently the latest versions of both the [[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737]] and [[Airbus A320]]) have been used for transatlantic service, meaning that city pairs between major North American hubs and secondary European cities can now be connected directly without the need for larger widebody jets, which were uneconomic on routes with lower passenger demand.\n\n== Transatlantic cables ==\n{{Further|Transatlantic communications cable}}\n\nTransatlantic cables are cables that have been laid along the ocean floor to connect North America and Europe. Before the advent of [[radio]], the only means of communication across the Atlantic Ocean was to physically connect the continents with a [[transatlantic telegraph cable]], the first of which was installed from [[Valentia Island|Valentia]], [[Ireland]] to [[Heart's Content, Newfoundland and Labrador|Heart's Content]], [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] in 1858. The first transatlantic telephone cable, [[TAT-1]], was installed in 1955.  The first transatlantic fiber optic cable, [[TAT-8]], was installed in 1988. The [[exchange rate]] between the [[United States dollar]] and [[Pound Sterling|British pound]] is still colloquially known as \"cable\" by financial marketeers, from the early use of the transatlantic cable for this purpose.\n\n==Transatlantic radio==\nTransatlantic radio communication was first accomplished on December 12, 1901 by [[Guglielmo Marconi]] who, using a temporary receiving station at [[Signal Hill (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Signal Hill, Newfoundland]], received a [[Morse code]] signal representing the letter \"S\" sent from [[Poldhu]], in [[Cornwall]], United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieeeghn.org/wiki/index.php/Milestones:Transmission_of_Transatlantic_Radio_Signals,_1901 |title=Milestones:Transmission of Transatlantic Radio Signals, 1901 |author= |date= |work=IEEE Global History Network |publisher=IEEE |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>  Guglielmo Marconi initiated commercial transatlantic radio communications between his high power long wave wireless telegraphy stations in [[Clifden]] Ireland and [[Glace Bay, Nova Scotia]] on 17 October 1907.\n\n[[Amateur radio]] operators are usually credited with the discovery of transatlantic radio communication in the [[shortwave]] bands. The first successful transatlantic tests were conducted by radio amateurs in December 1921 operating in the 200 meter medium-wave band, the shortest wavelength then available to amateurs. In 1922 hundreds of North American amateurs were heard in Europe at 200 meters and at least 20 North American amateurs heard amateur signals from Europe. The first two way transatlantic shortwave radio contacts were completed by radio amateurs in November 1923, on 110 meters.\n\nMarconi initiated the first commercial shortwave transatlantic radio communication between the UK to Canada using his ''[[Imperial Wireless Chain|Beam Wireless Service]]'' which went into commercial operation on 25 October 1926.  Shortwave radio vastly increased the speed and capacity of transatlantic communications at dramatically reduced cost compared to telegraph cable and long wave radio.\n\n[[Telstar]] was the first [[communications satellite]] to provide commercial transatlantic communications. It was launched by on July 10, 1962, the first privately sponsored space launch.  Communications satellites vastly increased the speed and quality of transatlantic communication, but transatlantic [[fiber optic]] cables have carried the vast majority of transatlantic communications traffic since the early 1990s.\n\n== Transatlantic tunnel ==\n{{Main|Transatlantic tunnel}}\nA Transatlantic Tunnel is a theoretical structure proposed several times since the late 19th century.  It would be a [[tunnel]] that spans the [[Atlantic Ocean]] between [[New York City]] and the [[United Kingdom]] or [[France]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transatlantic relations]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fowler Jr., William M. ''Steam Titans: Cunard, Collins, and the Epic Battle for Commerce on the North Atlantic'' (London: Bloomsbury), 2017. 358 pp\n* [https://theOceanpreneur.com/books Ocean Nomad: The Complete Atlantic Sailing Crew Guide]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{commons|North Atlantic Treaty Organisation}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=n-MDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA746&dq=Popular+Mechanics+1931+curtiss&hl=en&ei=nOz1TKGlGoT48AbhovSDBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Evolution of trans-Atlantic Ships\", May 1931, ''Popular Mechanics'']\n* [https://theoceanpreneur.com/sailing-the-atlantic-ocean/top-10-tips-for-sailing-across-the-atlantic-as-crew/ Sail Across the Atlantic as Crew]\n\n[[Category:International transport]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Atlantic Ocean|Crossing]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic relations|Crossing]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other uses of the term Transatlantic|Transatlantic (disambiguation){{!}}Transatlantic}}\n\n'''Transatlantic crossings''' are passages of passengers and cargo across the [[Atlantic Ocean]] between [[Europe]] or [[Africa]] and the [[Americas]]. The majority of passenger traffic is across the North Atlantic between [[Western Europe]] and [[North America]].  Centuries after the dwindling of sporadic [[Viking]] trade with [[Markland]], a regular and lasting transatlantic [[trade route]] was established in 1566 with the Spanish [[Spanish treasure fleet|West Indies fleets]], following the [[Voyages of Christopher Columbus]].\n\n== By sea ==\n{{Main|List of crossings of the Atlantic Ocean}}\nPrior to the 19th century, transatlantic crossings were undertaken in [[sailing ship]]s, and the journeys were time consuming and often perilous. The first trade route across the Atlantic was inaugurated by Spain a few decades after the European [[Discovery of the Americas]], with the establishment of the [[Spanish treasure fleet|West Indies fleets]] in 1566, a convoy system that regularly linked its territories in the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain|Americas]] with Spain for over two centuries. [[Portugal]] created a similar maritime route between its ports in [[Colonial Brazil|Brazil]] and the Portuguese mainland. Other colonial powers followed, such as [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Britain]], [[France]] and the [[Netherlands]], as they colonized the [[New World]].\n\nTransatlantic crossings became faster, safer, and more reliable with the advent of [[steamship]]s in the 19th century.  Grand [[ocean liner]]s began making regularly scheduled crossings, and soon it became a symbol of national and company status to build the largest, fastest, and most luxurious ocean liner for transatlantic crossings. The United States, United Kingdom, France, Germany and Italy built the most famous ocean liners.  Examples of some famous transatlantic liners are [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']] (had only made one voyage that was unsuccessful due to striking an iceberg),  {{RMS|Lusitania}}, {{RMS|Mauretania|1906|6}}, {{RMS|Olympic}}, {{SS|Rex}}, {{SS|America|1939|6}}, {{SS|United States}}, {{RMS|Queen Mary}}, {{SS|\u00cele de France}}, {{SS|Normandie}}, {{RMS|Queen Elizabeth}}, {{SS|France|1961|6}}, ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'', and {{RMS|Queen Mary 2}}.\n\nThe [[Blue Riband]] is awarded for the record fastest crossing by [[transatlantic liner]].  The current eastbound record was set by the American ocean liner ''[[SS United States|United States]]'' in July 1952: the ship made the crossing in  3 days, 10 hours, 40 minutes. ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' has awarded world records to various classes such as luxury liners, sail boats, and rowing boats.  Because of the shape of the continents and the assistance (or resistance) of ocean currents, the Eastbound crossing is quicker than the Westbound crossing.\n\nDuring World War II the transatlantic crossing was very important for the United Kingdom as much of Europe had been taken over by Germany and its allies preventing trade and supplies; the struggle is known as the [[Battle of the Atlantic]].\n\n===Crossings in small vessels===\n\n====Yacht=====\nThe late Tom Gentry set nearly every powerboat speed record in existence. His passion to win power boating's most coveted honor, the Blue Riband for the fastest passage across the Atlantic, drove him to design and build the 112', 11,500 horsepower Gentry Eagle. In 1989, he and a crew of five including his son, Norman Gentry, shattered the transatlantic crossing record and brought the honor back to the United States. Gentry took the Blue Riband away from the British airline and music tycoon Richard Branson. His record setting time of 62 hours & 7 minutes bested Sir Richard Branson's record by an astonishing 23%.\n\n\n====Zodiac====\nIn 1952, [[Alain Bombard]] crossed the Atlantic from East to West, spending 113 days adrift in a [[Zodiac Marine & Pool|Zodiac]], ''L'H\u00e9r\u00e9tique''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bombard|first=Alain|title=The Voyage of the Heretique|date=1953|publisher=Simon and Schuster}}</ref>\n\n====Rafts====\nIn 1956, [[L\u2019\u00c9gar\u00e9 II|Henri Beaudout]] crossed the Atlantic from West to East, from [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], on a raft of wood and rope, ''[[L\u2019\u00c9gar\u00e9 II]]'', in 88 days.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadden|first=Marie|title=Three Canadians, two kittens, one raft: A little-known journey across the Atlantic|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/three-canadians-two-kittens-one-raft-a-little-known-journey-across-the-atlantic/article4462515/|accessdate=19 May 2014|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, [[Thor Heyerdahl]] crossed the Atlantic in ''Ra II'', a [[papyrus]] raft built to an [[Ancient Egyptian]] design. This voyage followed an unsuccessful attempt the previous year in his first raft, ''Ra I''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heyerdahl |first=Thor |title=The Ra Expeditions |date=1972 |page= |isbn=0-14-003462-5}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the [[junk raft]], ''[[Son of Town Hall]]'', crossed the North Atlantic Ocean.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Son of Town Hall, First Raft made of Scrap to Cross the North Atlantic Ocean\n  | publisher = The Floating Neutrinos\n  | date = May 30, 2006\n  | url =  http://www.floatingneutrinos.com/son%20of%20town%20hall/chronology.htm\n  | accessdate = Sep 30, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Anthony Smith and the Antiki crossed the Atlantic.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Across the Atlantic - in a garden shed\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url =  http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2971402/Across-Atlantic-garden-shed-84-year-olds-settle-Saga-cruise-ancient-mariner-ideas.html\n  | accessdate = Mar 2, 2015}}\n</ref>\n\n==== Rowing and paddling====\nOn June 13, 2003, the French rower [[Maud Fontenoy]] started an eastward crossing of the Atlantic from [[Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon]]. She reached [[A Coru\u00f1a]] in Spain on October 10, becoming the first woman to accomplish this feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maudfontenoyfondation.com/en/ses-traversees-et-son-tour-du-monde.html |website=Fontenroy Foundation|title=Ses-traversees-et-son-tour-du-monde}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the [[Vivaldi Atlantic 4]] broke the previous rowing record of 55 days and setting a new record of 39 days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rowing the Atlantic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/northeast/series10/week3_vivaldi_atlantic_rowing.shtml |accessdate=29 August 2019 |agency=BBC |date=25 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2010, the Polish [[sexagenarian]] [[Aleksander Doba]] was the first recorded individual to complete a non-stop transatlantic crossing by [[kayak]]. He departed [[Dakar, Senegal]] and arrived in Brazil 99 days later.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/playbook/2011/02/epic-kayak-guy/ | title=64-Year-Old Kayaker Completes Trans-Atlantic Voyage | work=Wired | date=February 10, 2011 | accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref>\n=====Sail=====\n{{main|Transatlantic sailing record}}\n[[Image:Banque populaire5-003.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Banque Populaire V]], current record holder]]\nDuring the second half of the 19th century, more and more leisurely Atlantic crossings started to take place, especially with larger and more luxurious sailing yachts. Over the last century sailing has become more popular, and more accessible. What used to be an imposingly vast ocean has turned into an increasingly popular passage for ocean adventure travellers. With modern well-equipped boats, it has become a safer and more feasible undertaking than it was back in the day. Hundreds of sailing yachts make the Atlantic Ocean crossing each year. Most boats travel the North Atlantic starting from Europe to the Caribbean or South America. Some boats make the passage from Africa to the other side. From the Americas, boats mostly go to Europe. Several different routes exist. The most popular route is the North Atlantic circle, driven by the season and trade winds: the Southern route goes from east to west and the Northern route from west to east. A small but increasing number of yachts also make a high latitude voyage like the North West passage or cross the South Atlantic from Africa to Brazil <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoceanpreneur.com/books |website=Oceanpreneur|title=Ocean Nomad: The Atlantic Sailing Crew Guide}}</ref>\n\n=====Transatlantic rowing races=====\n{{Main|Atlantic Rowing Race}}\nIn 1997, the first East\u2013West Atlantic Rowing Race took place, running from the [[Canary Islands]] to the [[Caribbean]]. It now runs once every two years or so.{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn 2006, the first West\u2013East North Atlantic Rowing Race took place, running from [[New York City]] to [[Falmouth, Cornwall]] in the [[UK]].{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Transatlantic flights==\n{{Main|Transatlantic flight}}\nTransatlantic flight surpassed ocean liners as the predominant mode of crossing the Atlantic in the mid 20th century.  In 1919, the American [[NC-4]] became the first [[airplane]] to cross the Atlantic (but in multiple stages). Later that year, a British [[Vickers Vimy]] piloted by [[Alcock and Brown]] made the first non-stop transatlantic flight from [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] to [[Ireland]]. Also in 1919, the British were the first to cross the Atlantic in an [[airship]] when the [[R33 class airship|R34]] captained by Major George Herbert Scott of the [[Royal Air Force]] with his crew and passengers flew from East Fortune, Scotland  to Mineola, Long Island, covering a distance of about {{convert|3000|smi|km}} in about four and a half days; he then made a return trip to England, thus also completing the first double crossing of the Atlantic (east\u2013west\u2013east). The first aerial crossing of the South Atlantic was made by the Portuguese naval aviators [[Gago Coutinho]] and [[Sacadura Cabral]] in 1922. Coutinho and Cabral flew from [[Lisbon, Portugal]], to [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil in stages, using three different [[Fairey III]] biplanes, and they covered a distance of {{convert|8383|km}} between 30 March and 17 June. The first night-time crossing of the Atlantic was accomplished during 16\u201317 April 1927 by the Portuguese aviators [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Sarmento de Beires|Sarmento de Beires]], Jorge de Castilho and Manuel Gouveia, flying from the [[Bijag\u00f3s Archipelago]], [[Portuguese Guinea]], to [[Fernando de Noronha]], Brazil in the ''Argos'', a [[Dornier Do J|Dornier Wal]] flying boat. In May of 1927, [[Charles Lindbergh]] made the first solo non-stop transatlantic flight in an airplane (between [[New York City]] and [[Paris]]). The second solo piloting, and the first to carry a passenger, was [[Clarence Duncan Chamberlin]] on June 6, 1927. [[Edward R. Armstrong]] proposed a string of anchored \"seadromes\" to refuel planes in a crossing.\n\nThe first serious attempt to take a share of the transatlantic passenger market away from the ocean liners was undertaken by [[Germany]]. In the 1930s, Germany crossed the Atlantic with [[Zeppelin]]s that could carry about 60 passengers in a similar luxurious style to the ocean liners. However, the [[Hindenburg disaster|''Hindenburg'' disaster]] in 1937 put an end to transatlantic Zeppelin flights.\n\nOn June 1, 1944, two [[K class blimp|K-class blimps]] from Blimp Squadron ZP-14 of the [[United States Navy]] (USN) completed the first transatlantic crossing by [[Blimp|non-rigid airships]]. The two K-ships (K-123 and K-130) left [[South Weymouth Naval Air Station|South Weymouth, MA]] on May 28, 1944 and flew approximately 16 hours to [[Naval Station Argentia]], Newfoundland.  From Argentia, the blimps flew approximately 22 hours to [[Lajes Field]] on Terceira Island in the Azores.  The final leg of the first transatlantic crossing was about a 20-hour flight from the Azores to [[Kenitra Airport|Craw Field]] in Port Lyautey ([[Kenitra]]), French [[Morocco]].<ref>Kline, R. C. and Kubarych, S. J., Blimpron 14 Overseas, 1944, Naval Historical Center, Navy Yard, Washington, D. C.</ref><ref>https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/fbd712_4eac320cdad44dd68701e9cecad8e446.pdf</ref>\n\nBeginning in the 1950s, the predominance of ocean liners began to wane when larger, [[jet engine|jet]]-powered airplanes began carrying passengers across the ocean in less and less time.  The speed of crossing the ocean therefore became more important than the style of crossing it.  The maturing passenger [[Jet Age]] starting with the [[Boeing 707]] reduced the typical crossing time between [[London]] and [[New York City]] to between 6.5 and 8 hours, depending on weather conditions.  By the 1970s, supersonic [[Concorde]] airplanes could connect the two cities in less than 4 hours, and only one ocean liner, ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' remained on the transatlantic route for those who favored the slower style of travel. \n\nThe economics of commercial transatlantic flying have evolved markedly since the 1950s; the introduction of [[Wide-body aircraft|widebody]] airliners (such as the [[Boeing 747]] and [[Douglas DC-10]]) in the early 1970s made affordable transatlantic travel to the masses a reality.  Since the 1990s, the high [[reliability engineering|reliability]] of modern jet engines has meant that twin engine jet aircraft such as the [[Boeing 767]], [[Boeing 777]] and [[Airbus A330]] have largely taken over on transatlantic routes from quad-engine jets, whilst the supersonic Concorde was ultimately doomed by its high running costs, leading to its retirement in 2003.  Since the late 1990s, single aisle, narrow body jet airliners (starting with the [[Boeing 757]], and more recently the latest versions of both the [[Boeing 737 MAX|Boeing 737]] and [[Airbus A320]]) have been used for transatlantic service, meaning that city pairs between major North American hubs and secondary European cities can now be connected directly without the need for larger widebody jets, which were uneconomic on routes with lower passenger demand.\n\n== Transatlantic cables ==\n{{Further|Transatlantic communications cable}}\n\nTransatlantic cables are cables that have been laid along the ocean floor to connect North America and Europe. Before the advent of [[radio]], the only means of communication across the Atlantic Ocean was to physically connect the continents with a [[transatlantic telegraph cable]], the first of which was installed from [[Valentia Island|Valentia]], [[Ireland]] to [[Heart's Content, Newfoundland and Labrador|Heart's Content]], [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] in 1858. The first transatlantic telephone cable, [[TAT-1]], was installed in 1955.  The first transatlantic fiber optic cable, [[TAT-8]], was installed in 1988. The [[exchange rate]] between the [[United States dollar]] and [[Pound Sterling|British pound]] is still colloquially known as \"cable\" by financial marketeers, from the early use of the transatlantic cable for this purpose.\n\n==Transatlantic radio==\nTransatlantic radio communication was first accomplished on December 12, 1901 by [[Guglielmo Marconi]] who, using a temporary receiving station at [[Signal Hill (Newfoundland and Labrador)|Signal Hill, Newfoundland]], received a [[Morse code]] signal representing the letter \"S\" sent from [[Poldhu]], in [[Cornwall]], United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieeeghn.org/wiki/index.php/Milestones:Transmission_of_Transatlantic_Radio_Signals,_1901 |title=Milestones:Transmission of Transatlantic Radio Signals, 1901 |author= |date= |work=IEEE Global History Network |publisher=IEEE |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>  Guglielmo Marconi initiated commercial transatlantic radio communications between his high power long wave wireless telegraphy stations in [[Clifden]] Ireland and [[Glace Bay, Nova Scotia]] on 17 October 1907.\n\n[[Amateur radio]] operators are usually credited with the discovery of transatlantic radio communication in the [[shortwave]] bands. The first successful transatlantic tests were conducted by radio amateurs in December 1921 operating in the 200 meter medium-wave band, the shortest wavelength then available to amateurs. In 1922 hundreds of North American amateurs were heard in Europe at 200 meters and at least 20 North American amateurs heard amateur signals from Europe. The first two way transatlantic shortwave radio contacts were completed by radio amateurs in November 1923, on 110 meters.\n\nMarconi initiated the first commercial shortwave transatlantic radio communication between the UK to Canada using his ''[[Imperial Wireless Chain|Beam Wireless Service]]'' which went into commercial operation on 25 October 1926.  Shortwave radio vastly increased the speed and capacity of transatlantic communications at dramatically reduced cost compared to telegraph cable and long wave radio.\n\n[[Telstar]] was the first [[communications satellite]] to provide commercial transatlantic communications. It was launched by on July 10, 1962, the first privately sponsored space launch.  Communications satellites vastly increased the speed and quality of transatlantic communication, but transatlantic [[fiber optic]] cables have carried the vast majority of transatlantic communications traffic since the early 1990s.\n\n== Transatlantic tunnel ==\n{{Main|Transatlantic tunnel}}\nA Transatlantic Tunnel is a theoretical structure proposed several times since the late 19th century.  It would be a [[tunnel]] that spans the [[Atlantic Ocean]] between [[New York City]] and the [[United Kingdom]] or [[France]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Transatlantic relations]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fowler Jr., William M. ''Steam Titans: Cunard, Collins, and the Epic Battle for Commerce on the North Atlantic'' (London: Bloomsbury), 2017. 358 pp\n* [https://theOceanpreneur.com/books Ocean Nomad: The Complete Atlantic Sailing Crew Guide]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{commons|North Atlantic Treaty Organisation}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=n-MDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA746&dq=Popular+Mechanics+1931+curtiss&hl=en&ei=nOz1TKGlGoT48AbhovSDBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=true \"Evolution of trans-Atlantic Ships\", May 1931, ''Popular Mechanics'']\n* [https://theoceanpreneur.com/sailing-the-atlantic-ocean/top-10-tips-for-sailing-across-the-atlantic-as-crew/ Sail Across the Atlantic as Crew]\n\n[[Category:International transport]]\n[[Category:Transport in the Atlantic Ocean|Crossing]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic relations|Crossing]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: time consuming \u2192 time-consuming, May of 1927 \u2192 May 1927", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transatlantic_crossing"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Chile}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Chile (Density).svg\n| legend1         = Map of regions with confirmed coronavirus cases ('''as of 6 April'''): {{legend|#FCEED3|1\u20139 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|1000\u20139999 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Chile]]\n| first_case      = [[Talca]]\n| arrival_date    = 3 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=03|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = \n| recovery_cases  = 528\n| deaths          = 34<ref name=\"Deaths\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.emol.com/noticias/Nacional/2020/03/31/981612/Minsal-nuevo-balance-covid19.html|title=Minsal reporta cuatro nuevos fallecidos por covid-19 y v\u00edctimas llegan a 12: Hay 2.738 casos registrados |website=emol.com |date=31 March 2020 }}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 4,471<ref name=\"Govt_Report\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/ minsal.cl: Nuevo Coronavirus COVID-19]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Chile]] on March 2020.<ref name=\"First_Case\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry-idUSKBN20Q2UU |title=Chile records first confirmed case of coronavirus: health ministry |access-date=3 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305082641/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry-idUSKBN20Q2UU |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of |2020|3}} there is a considerable [[COVID-19]] outbreak in Chile. While initial cases had been imported from [[South East Asia]] and [[Europe]], they expanded into a sizeable quantity of untraceable infections, placing the country within phase 4 of the pandemic as defined by the [[WHO]], and surpassing a thousand confirmed cases in 25 March 2020. The potential for an increase of Coronavirus cases in Chile is vast, especially given the [[2019\u201320 Chilean protests|continuing mass protests]].\n\n== Timeline ==\n*'''3 March 2020''': The Minister of Public Health confirmed the first case of the [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus in Chile, thus making the country the third in [[Latin America]] to report such an instance after [[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]],<ref name=\"First_Case\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24horas.cl/nacional/confirman-primer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-paciente-esta-en-talca-3990369|title=Confirman primer caso de coronavirus en Chile: paciente est\u00e1 en Talca|date=3 March 2020|website=24Horas.cl|language=es|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> the latter reporting its first case a few hours prior. Patient zero is a 33-year-old man in the city of [[Talca]].<ref name=\"usnews\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-03-03/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry |title=Chile Records First Confirmed Case of Coronavirus: Health Ministry |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''4 March 2020'''; The regional secretary (Seremi), Marlenne Dur\u00e1n, confirmed the second case of COVID-19 in the country. The new patient being the wife of the 33-year-old doctor who was diagnosed positive the previous day.<ref name=\"2nd_Case\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.chvnoticias.cl/trending/esposa-segundo-caso-coronavirus-chile_20200304/ |title=Esposa de m\u00e9dico con coronavirus tambi\u00e9n est\u00e1 contagiada |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, the Ministry of Health confirmed a third case in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]; a 56-year-old woman, who returned to Chile after traveling to Europe, where she visited several countries, including Italy.<ref name=\"Case_3\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/tercer-caso-coronavirus-chile-region-metropolitana_20200304/ |title=Ministerio de Salud confirma el tercer caso de coronavirus en Chile: Paciente reside en la Regi\u00f3n Metropolitana|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''5 March 2020''': The Public Health Institute (ISP) confirmed a fourth case in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]; a 40-year-old woman who entered Chile on 29 February from Italy.<ref name=\"Case_4\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/confirman-cuarto-caso-coronavirus-chile_20200305/ |title=Confirman cuarto caso de coronavirus en Chile|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''6 March 2020''': The Ministry of Health confirmed a fifth case in Santiago; a 58-year-old man who travelled to Europe alongside patient n\u00b03.<ref name=\"Case_5\">{{cite news |title=Confirman quinto caso de Coronavirus Covid-19 en Chile: es la pareja de una de las contagiadas|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2020/03/06/confirman-quinto-caso-de-coronavirus-covid-19-en-chile-es-la-pareja-de-una-de-las-contagiadas.shtml |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=BioBio Chile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Radio BioBio |date=6 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''7 March 2020''': The Ministry of Health confirmed a sixth case; a 17-year-old male related to patients n\u00b03 and 5 who travelled to Europe alongside them.<ref name=\"Case_6\">{{cite news |title=Ministerio de Salud confirma sexto caso de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.24horas.cl/nacional/ministerio-de-salud-confirma-sexto-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-4002978 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=24 Horas Chile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=24 horas |date=7 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Later that same day, a 20-year-old woman from [[Puerto Montt]] was confirmed as the 7th case in the country.<ref name=\"Case_7\">{{cite news |title=Minsal confirma s\u00e9ptimo caso de coronavirus en Chile: es el primero en la regi\u00f3n de Los Lagos|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/07/minsal-confirma-septimo-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-se-trata-de-joven-de-20-anos.shtml |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBio |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=BioBio Chile |date=7 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''8 March 2020''': 3 more cases were confirmed; an 83-year-old woman who contracted the virus from a family member that visited her from [[New York (state)|New York]], who in turn, later presented symptoms and was diagnosed with COVID-19 upon arrival to the United States<ref name=\"Case_8\">{{cite news |title=Confirman octavo caso de Coronavirus COVID-19 en Chile: es una persona de 83 a\u00f1os|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/08/confirman-octavo-caso-de-coronavirus-covid-19-en-chile-es-una-persona-de-83-anos.shtml |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBio |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=BioBio Chile |date=8 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> (Possibly making this the first infection to occur entirely within Chilean soil); a 39-year-old man from Talca related to the 1st and 2nd cases who had contracted the virus via contact with them,<ref name=\"Case_9\">{{cite news |title=Confirman octavo caso de Coronavirus COVID-19 en Chile: es una persona de 83 a\u00f1os|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/minsal-confirma-noveno-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile/LJXNH57SYVH4HFLIXI3SQAIONE/ |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=La Tercera |date=8 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> and a 14-year-old male who travelled to Europe with patients n\u00b03, 5 and 6.\n*'''9 March 2020''': The Ministry of health reported 3 new cases; a 42-year-old man from Santiago, a 2-year-old infant belonging to the Maule cluster and a 38-year-old man from [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], marking the first case within the [[Biob\u00edo Region]]. Along with the news, the Ministry of Health announced that it will start reporting new cases on a daily basis instead of one-by-one as they get confirmed.<ref name=\"Cases_11-13\">{{cite news |title=Confirman 13 casos de coronavirus en Chile: Minsal establece colaboraci\u00f3n con las FF.AA.|url=https://www.chvnoticias.cl/trending/13-casos-coronavirus-minsal-colaboracion-ff-aa_20200309/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Chilevisi\u00f3n noticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Chilevisi\u00f3n |date=9 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=\"COVID-19 MINSAL data\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Ministerio de Salud |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Minsal |date=9 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''10 March 2020''': 4 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 17; 5 of which belong to a small cluster from San Benito school in [[Vitacura]] that can be traced to a family who had travelled to Europe, as well as a man who had contact with a person who had recently been to [[Spain]]. The infected students have been quarantined and the Ministry of Health has placed the school under observation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cinco de los 17 casos de coronavirus est\u00e1n ligados a un colegio de Vitacura|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/cinco-de-los-17-casos-de-coronavirus-estan-ligados-a-un-colegio-de-vitacura/3UA6ZKHTYFA2NJUAGLBQ5RD4EI/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=La Tercera|date=10 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''11 March 2020''': 6 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 23. Among the infected, 14 reside in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]], becoming the first region in Chile to surpass ten confirmed cases.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n*'''12 March 2020''': 11 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 34. These new cases were reported in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]], specifically concentrated in the communes of [[Las Condes]], [[Vitacura]] and [[Lo Barnechea]].<ref name=\"Cases_33\">{{cite news |title=Casos de coronavirus en Chile aumentan a 33 personas|url=https://www.df.cl/noticias/empresas/salud/casos-de-coronavirus-en-chile-aumentan-a-33-personas/2020-03-12/111740.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Chilevisi\u00f3n noticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=df.cl|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn_Case_33\">{{cite news |title=10 nuevos casos: Minsal reporta que hay 33 infectados de Covid-19 en Chile|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/coronavirus-minsal-33-infectados-covid19-chile_20200312/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=cnnchile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> An additional case was also reported in [[Talca]].<ref name=\"Cases_34\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Chile: Confirman nuevo caso en Talca y cifra de contagiados aumenta a 34|url=https://www.latercera.com/que-pasa/noticia/coronavirus-en-chile-confirman-nuevo-caso-en-talca-y-cifra-de-contagiados-aumenta-a-34/TGQOT7SG4FFNRGSU4DAD2JERHI/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=latercera.com|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''13 March 2020''': 9 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 43.<ref name=\"Cases_43\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Confirman primeros 2 casos en Concepci\u00f3n y total nacional de contagios llega a 43|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/13/covid-19-confirman-primeros-2-casos-en-concepcion-y-total-nacional-de-contagios-llega-a-4.shtml |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBi\u00edo |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=biobiochile.cl|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> [[Saint George's College, Santiago|Saint George's College]] began a 15-day quarantine period after a teacher tested positive to the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Colegio de Vitacura entra en cuarentena por coronavirus|url=https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2020/03/13/colegio-de-vitacura-entra-en-cuarentena-por-coronavirus.html|accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Radio Agricultura |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=radioagricultura.cl|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''14 March 2020''': 18 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 61.<ref name=\"Cases_61a\">{{cite news |title=Chile entra en fase 3: Aumentan a 61 los casos coronavirus y aparecen los primeros en el norte|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/61-casos-coronavirus-chile_20200314/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=14 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The Ministry of health detailed that there are four new cases in three regions, which are [[Antofagasta]] (2 cases), [[Atacama]] (1) and [[Ays\u00e9n Region|Ays\u00e9n]] (1), the latter being an 83-year-old British tourist aboard a cruise ship that landed in [[Coyhaique]] after showing symptoms of COVID-19, having previously disembarked in [[Caleta Tortel]]. The rest of the 14 new cases of COVID-19 infection are located in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]] (11), Maule (1) and \u00d1uble (2).<ref name=\"Cases_61\">{{cite news |title=Se sumaron tres regiones: Minsal aumenta a 61 los casos confirmados de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/294876-ministerio-de-salud-coronavirus-casos-confirmados-contagiados-chile-balance.html |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=meganoticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=14 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''15 March 2020''': 14 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 75.<ref name=\"Cases_75\">{{cite news |title=Nuevo reporte eleva a 75 los casos de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/nuevo-reporte-75-casos-coronavirus-chile_20200315/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=15 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''16 March 2020''': 81 new cases were confirmed in a single day, bringing the total up to 156. According to the definition of the Health Organization (WHO), the start of stage 4 of the pandemic has been initiated.<ref name=\"Cases_155\">{{cite news |title=Chile entra en Fase 4: 155 casos de coronavirus y Gobierno anuncia cierre de fronteras\n|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/16/chile-entra-en-fase-4-155-casos-de-coronavirus-y-gobierno-anuncia-cierre-de-fronteras.shtml |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=16 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''17 March 2020''': 45 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 201.<ref name=\"Cases_201\">{{cite news |title=Ministro de Salud confirma 201 casos de personas contagiadas de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295181-ministro-de-salud-jaime-manalich-201-casos-contagios-coronavirus-chile.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=17 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> It was also determined that the virus spread through the +20 cases cluster in Chill\u00e1n via direct and indirect interpersonal contact within a gym, which was later closed and sanitized. Its users have been placed in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gimnasio fue foco de varios contagios de coronavirus en Chill\u00e1n|url=https://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/pais/region-de-nuble/gimnasio-fue-foco-de-varios-contagios-de-coronavirus-en-chillan/2020-03-17/145451.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Radio Cooperativa|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cooperativa.cl|date=17 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''18 March 2020''': 37 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 238.<ref name=\"Cases_238\">{{cite news |title=Sube a 238 la cifra de contagiados por coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295317-coronavirus-ministro-salud-jaime-manalich-238-casos-contagios-chile.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=18 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The Maule region became the third to surpass 10 cases.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n*'''19 March 2020''': 103 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 342.<ref name=\"Cases_342\">{{cite news |title=Chile suma 103 nuevos casos de coronavirus y cifra de contagios llega a 342|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295456-balance-casos-coronavirus-chile-342-jaime-manalich.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=19 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The same day, patients zero and 1 (The 33-year-old man from Talca and his wife, both who had travelled to Southeast Asia) were ruled as healthy and sent back home to begin a post-recovery quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title='Caso cero' del COVID-19 en Chile fue dado de alta|url=https://rpp.pe/mundo/chile/coronavirus-caso-cero-del-covid-19-en-chile-fue-dado-de-alta-noticia-1252636?ref=rpp |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=RPP|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=rpp.pe|date=19 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''20 March 2020''': 92 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 434.<ref name=\"Cases_434\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Chile: nuevos casos y \u00faltimas noticias de hoy en vivo|url=https://chile.as.com/chile/2020/03/20/tikitakas/1584701975_596888.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=chile.as.com|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=chile.as.com|date=20 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''21 March 2020''': 103 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 537 nationwide. Health Minister Jaime Ma\u00f1alich confirmed the first death derived from coronavirus infection in Chile; an 83-year-old woman from Santiago.<ref name=\"Cases_537\">{{cite news |title=Ministro Ma\u00f1alich confirm\u00f3 muerte de la primera persona contagiada por coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295726-manalich-coronavirus-primera-muerte-en-chile-mujer-83-anos-postrada-manejo-compasivo.html|accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=meganoticias.cl|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=21 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n*'''22 March 2020''': 95 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 632. Nationwide wide night time curfew was imposed.<ref name=\"Cases_632\"/>\n*'''24 March 2020''': The first case in [[Easter Island|Easter Island (Rapa Nui)]] is reported, despite the lockdown established on 19 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/de-origen-autoctono-rapa-nui-confirma-primer-contagio-de-coronavirus-en-la-isla_20200324/|title=De origen aut\u00f3ctono: Rapa Nui confirma primer contagio de coronavirus en la isla|publisher=CNN Chile|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref> 176 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 922.<ref name=\"Cases_922\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|publisher=Minsal|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n*'''25 March 2020''': 220 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,142 and 3, respecitvely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.futuro.cl/2020/03/minsal-informo-de-1142-casos-de-coronavirus-en-chile-con-tercer-fallecido/|title=Minsal inform\u00f3 de 1142 casos de coronavirus en Chile con tercer fallecido|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n*'''26 March 2020''': 164 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,306 and 4, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://chile.as.com/chile/2020/03/26/tikitakas/1585219333_248806.html/|title=Coronavirus en Chile: 1306 casos, 4 muertes y noticias 26 de marzo|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref> Total curfew to 7 communes of the Metropolitan Region was imposed.<ref name=\"Cases_1306\">{{cite news |title=Plan de Acci\u00f3n por Coronavirus|url=https://www.gob.cl/coronavirus/plandeaccion/|publisher=Chilean Government|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n*'''27 March 2020''': 304 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,610 and 5, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=28 March 2020|work=|accessdate=27 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref> Total curfew to Araucania Region was imposed due to high increase on new     cases.<ref name=\"Cases_1610\">{{cite news |title=Plan de Acci\u00f3n por Coronavirus|url=https://www.gob.cl/coronavirus/plandeaccion/|publisher=Chilean Government|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n*'''28 March 2020''': 299 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,909 and 6, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=28 March 2020|work=|accessdate=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n*'''29 March 2020''': 230 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 2,139 and 7, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=29 March 2020|work=|accessdate=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n==Case summary==\n\n=== Region-wise details ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Chile medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Region-wise summary ===\n* ''Updated as of 5 April 2020''.<ref name=\"Govt_Report\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Ministerio de Salud|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Gobierno de Chile|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Regions\n!Confirmed cases\n!Confirmed deaths\n|-\n|{{Flag|Arica y Parinacota}}\n|28\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Tarapac\u00e1}}\n|20\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Antofagasta}}\n|60\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Atacama}}\n|5\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Coquimbo}}\n|50\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Valpara\u00edso}}\n|191\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Santiago Metropolitan Region}}\n|2102\n|10\n|-\n|{{Flag|O'Higgins}}\n|41\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Maule Region}}\n|103\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|\u00d1uble Region}}\n|425\n|3\n|-\n|{{Flag|Biob\u00edo Region}}\n|365\n|2\n|-\n|[[Image:Flag of La Araucania, Chile.svg|23px|border]] [[Araucan\u00eda Region]]\n|509\n|13\n|-\n|[[Image:Flag of Los R\u00edos, Chile.svg|23px|border]] [[Los R\u00edos Region]]\n|99\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Los Lagos Region}}\n|276\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Ays\u00e9n}}\n|7\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Magallanes}}\n|190\n|2\n|-\n! Total: 16 regions\n! 4471 confirmed cases\n! 34 confirmed deaths\n|}\n\n== Statistics ==\n* ''{{As of|2020|4|6|df=}} there are 4815 confirmed cases in Chile''.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Chile medical cases chart}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 50px;\" | Day\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 250px;\" | New cases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 225px;\" | Cumulative cases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 225px;\" | Cumulative recovered\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 225px;\" | Cumulative death\n|-\n| {{dts|3 March 2020}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|4 March 2020}} || 2 || 3 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|5 March 2020}} || 1 || 4 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|6 March 2020}} || 1 || 5 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|7 March 2020}} || 2 || 7 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|8 March 2020}} 